s of human belonging and care than the white nationalist loyalties early U.S. capitalism encouraged. In this lucid work, Day makes Azusa's challenge to this warped economic ecology visible, showing how Azusa not only offered a radical critique of racial capitalism but also offers a way for contemporary religious communities to cultivate democratic practices of belonging against the backdrop of late capitalism's deep racial divisions and material inequalities.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aAfrican AmericanszCaliforniazLos AngelesxReligion. 0aCapitalismxReligious aspectsxChristianity. 0aDemocracyxReligious aspectsxChristianity. 0aPentecostalismzUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aRacismxReligious aspectsxChristianity. 0aRevivalszCaliforniazLos AngelesxHistoryy20th century. 7aRELIGION / Christianity / History.2bisacsh  aAzusa Revival.  aBlack Women.  aDemocracy.  aErotic.  aPentecostalism.  aRacial Capitalism.  aSlave Religion.  aWhite Supremacy.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2022 Englishz978311099389908iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2022z9783110994810oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Classical Studies 2022 Englishz978311099291508iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Classical Studies 2022z9783110992878oZDB-23-DGD08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertStanford University Press Complete eBook-Package 2022z97831107664860 cprintz978150361523640uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978150363163240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781503631632423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781503631632/original  a978-3-11-076648-6  Stanford University Press Complete eBook-Package 2022b2022  a978-3-11-099291-5